<DOC><DOCNO> AP881012-0204 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2143EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Israel-China 1stLd-Writethru a0647 10-12 0403</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Israel-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0410</SECOND><HEAD>Israel, China Sign Trade Deal, Plan Diplomatic Relations</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with announcement by Foreign Ministry andnew detail</NOTE><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Israel and China will establish diplomaticrelations soon, but the timing depends on progress in Middle Eastpeace negotiations, the Israeli Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.   Israel television said officials of the two governments signed atrade agreement Wednesday in Beijing. State radio said each sideestablished government-run corporations to promote trade.   Avraham Tamir, director-general of the Foreign Ministry, said onIsrael television that diplomatic ties with China hinged on how theMiddle East peace process advances. He added that efforts toachieve peace in the region would continue and ties with Chinawould be a reality ``in the very near future.''   He confirmed news reports that Israel would establish anacademic center in Beijing but denied the first official Israeliinstitution to be set up in China would have a political purpose.   The state television report said Yitzhak Minervi, the ministry'stop economic official, signed the trade agreement on behalf ofprivate Israeli companies.   It said the governments soon would begin negotiating anagreement for Chinese coal exports to Israel. In the past, Chinahas rejected requests to sell coal directly to Israel.   Maariv, an independent daily newspaper, said the new Israelitrading company was called Copeco and 20 possible projects wereunder study. A government official, who spoke on condition ofanonymity, said they focused on agriculture, medicine and medicaltechnology.   Israel radio described the two companies as ``virtual chambersof commerce or interest sections.''   Three Israeli academics are in China to discuss the Middle Eastsituation. One of them, Professor Galia Golan of Hebrew University,said in a radio interview the moves toward cooperation represent aChinese effort ``to increase contacts with Israel and to try towarm relations on a semi-official basis.''   ``The signal they are definitely giving is that, short ofdiplomatic relations, they would like to improve contacts withIsrael,'' she said.   On Tuesday, the daily Jerusalem Post said 30 members of thePeking Opera will perform in Israel next May under a contractsigned in Belgium by Israeli and Chinese officials.   There have been reports of arms trade between the two countries,not confirmed by either side. The Sunday Times of London has saidIsraeli military technicians were modernizing Soviet-built tanksand heavy artillery used by the Chinese army.</TEXT></DOC>